WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:33.500
<v Casey>Hey, welcome back. On today's episode — a mural going up on the Central Cariboo Arts Centre in Williams Lake, an evacuation order expanding out past Fiftynine Creek, two new fires burning out of control near Anahim Lake, and a question we haven't asked yet on this show: when a small Cariboo community decides what gets built in its public space, who actually holds the pen? Horsefly's about to find out. That and more, coming right up.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:22.799
<v Casey>Welcome to Cariboo Signals, an AI-generated review of the latest tech news and ideas that impact our rural communities — I'm Casey. It's Saturday, July 18th, 2026. Coming to you from the Cariboo, on lands that have been cared for by the Secwépemc, Tŝilhqot'in, and Dakelh peoples since time immemorial. Today's theme is Cariboo Local Affairs.

00:01:23.099 --> 00:01:35.956
<v Riley>And I'm Riley. Today we're staying close to home — councils, budgets, arts centres, and who actually gets a say when a Cariboo town decides what it wants to become.

00:01:36.656 --> 00:01:41.370
<v Casey>Let's get into what's actually happening on the ground this week.

00:01:41.670 --> 00:02:00.098
<v Casey>We'll start with something that touches every rural inbox eventually. The Verge is reporting a Florida man's been arrested for allegedly stealing over $200,000 in crypto by hiding malware inside fake Steam games — thousands of victims infected before anyone noticed the pattern.

00:02:01.598 --> 00:02:27.312
<v Riley>TechCrunch has the fuller version of the same arrest — 21-year-old Zyaire Wilkins, accused of publishing several fake indie games on Steam laced with malware that quietly drained crypto wallets linked to infected machines. Federal prosecutors say the scheme ran under everyone's nose because Steam's storefront doesn't vet every small developer's upload the way an app store curates its listings.

00:02:27.612 --> 00:02:36.183
<v Casey>Rural angle — same digital literacy gap we talk about with phishing scams, just wearing a gaming skin this time.

00:02:36.483 --> 00:03:07.340
<v Riley>Right, and it's worth remembering the fix isn't complicated. Don't download unverified indie games from unknown publishers, and don't link a wallet to a machine you can't fully audit. That's not rural-specific advice, it's just internet hygiene — but it lands harder here because there's less local IT support to call when something goes sideways, and a lot of Cariboo households are on shared family computers where one bad download hits everyone.

00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:30.697
<v Casey>Closer to home — and this is the story we're watching most closely today. The Williams Lake Tribune has an update on the Fiftynine Creek wildfire. It's grown to roughly 4,000 hectares as of Friday evening, and the evacuation order has been expanded to cover additional properties near the fire perimeter.

00:03:30.997 --> 00:03:39.997
<v Riley>That's a serious jump in a short window. What's the source of the growth — wind driven, or just dry fuel?

00:03:40.297 --> 00:04:12.011
<v Casey>Reporter Brendan Shykora's coverage points to hot, dry conditions and shifting winds pushing the fire edge faster than crews anticipated. BC Wildfire Service has ground crews and air support working the perimeter where visibility allows, but for anyone in the affected zone, Emergency Info BC and the Cariboo Regional District's own alert system are the two places to check status — not social media rumours, which tend to spread faster than the fire itself.

00:04:13.211 --> 00:04:37.639
<v Riley>And the same day, the Tribune's also reporting two wildfires north of Anahim Lake — out in the Chilcotin, northeast of Lessard Lake, roughly 347 kilometres west of Williams Lake — that are currently listed as out of control. No evacuation order there yet, but given how fast Fiftynine Creek moved this week, that's worth watching closely.

00:04:37.939 --> 00:04:58.081
<v Casey>Two fire fronts burning in one region in one week. That's exactly the kind of week the regional district's emergency operations centre exists for, and exactly the kind of week that tests whether the alert systems we've talked about on this show actually reach people in time.

00:04:59.281 --> 00:05:16.423
<v Riley>Sticking with community infrastructure but on a much lighter note — CFJC Today Kamloops has a story on the Kamloops Legion unveiling a new veterans' crosswalk this week, a painted crossing near the Legion hall meant to honour local veterans.

00:05:16.723 --> 00:05:30.008
<v Casey>We covered a similar project in Williams Lake a few weeks back — different city, same model, right down to the Legion doing the fundraising and municipal crews handling the install.

00:05:30.308 --> 00:05:53.879
<v Riley>It suggests this is becoming a template regional Legions are replicating branch to branch. Once one town proves the concept works — permitting, paint supplier, sign-off — the next Legion down the highway doesn't have to start from scratch. That's actually a nice small example of institutional knowledge travelling between towns without anyone formalizing it.

00:05:55.379 --> 00:06:17.664
<v Casey>Shifting into industry — there's a cluster of mining stories today worth grouping together, because they all point the same direction. The Northern Miner is reporting Canada's first diamond mine, Ekati in the Northwest Territories, is shutting down after a BC Supreme Court ruling placed its owner, Arctic Canadian Diamond, into receivership.

00:06:17.964 --> 00:06:39.392
<v Riley>And the same outlet has a piece on Cuba's cobalt supply exposing a Western weak spot — Canada's largest cobalt refinery is taking a hit from US sanctions on Cuban imports, which is a reminder that critical mineral supply chains are only as strong as the geopolitics sitting underneath them.

00:06:39.692 --> 00:06:54.263
<v Casey>Then there's a third Northern Miner story — investment firm Sprott's read that AI data centres are becoming a new driver of rare earth demand, stacking on top of existing military and clean-energy consumption.

00:06:54.563 --> 00:07:28.848
<v Riley>Three stories, one thread: the minerals powering both the green transition and the AI boom are getting squeezed from multiple directions at once — sanctions, receivership, and demand spikes nobody priced in five years ago. None of that touches the Cariboo directly today, but this region has a mining history and current mining employment, so when global supply chains wobble, it's not an abstract headline here — it's a payroll question in towns like Wells or along the Barkerville corridor.

00:07:30.348 --> 00:07:56.919
<v Casey>Also worth noting today — BC Gov News says the province, the federal government, and the municipality of Grand Forks are partnering on flood-mitigation projects after past flooding events there. It's the same three-jurisdiction funding model — municipal, provincial, federal — that shows up again and again whenever a small BC community needs infrastructure bigger than its own tax base can cover.

00:07:57.219 --> 00:08:23.790
<v Riley>And speaking of things bigger than any one jurisdiction — Xi Jinping made a public push this week for more open-source AI development, framing China as, quote, "ready to be more open" on model architecture. Worth watching given how much of the global AI conversation up to now has assumed a closed, proprietary path forward, especially out of the big American labs.

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:49.375
<v Casey>CNET has a related report — testing shows AI chatbot responses often mirror the censorship posture of whatever government's jurisdiction the training data leans on. A reminder that "the AI said so" isn't a neutral source, wherever in the world you're asking the question, and a good one for anyone treating chatbots as some kind of universal reference desk.

00:08:50.475 --> 00:09:05.474
<v Riley>Also in the bonus pile — NYT Business is reporting stocks dipped this week on investor anxiety about AI spending, with growing unease over competition from Chinese AI labs eating into the assumed American lead.

00:09:05.774 --> 00:09:25.059
<v Casey>And TechRadar's covering the flip side of that story — a new Chinese model called Kimi K3 that's apparently turning heads specifically because it's open and reportedly strong at coding, which is the kind of thing that makes a "we're ahead" narrative harder to sustain.

00:09:25.959 --> 00:09:41.816
<v Riley>And on a lighter note to close out the roundup — ScienceDaily has astronomers catching a sun-like star that appears to have eaten one of its own planets, leaving a lithium fingerprint behind as the forensic evidence.

00:09:42.116 --> 00:09:46.401
<v Casey>Cosmic cannibalism as a Saturday palate cleanser. Sure, why not.

00:09:46.701 --> 00:09:47.701
<v Riley>Ha. Onward.

00:09:48.001 --> 00:09:57.001
<v Casey>That's the roundup for today — let's talk about who's actually doing the work on the ground here in the Cariboo.

00:09:57.301 --> 00:10:35.872
<v Riley>Today's spotlight is on the Cariboo Memorial Hospital Foundation, a volunteer-driven group in Williams Lake that's raised nearly four million dollars over the years for hospital equipment the regional health authority budget doesn't always stretch to cover — imaging tools, patient monitors, the kind of gear that actually changes outcomes in a rural emergency room. It's entirely community-funded, entirely volunteer-run, and it's been doing this quietly for years without a lot of fanfare. If you want to see where local giving goes further than most donation drives, check out cmhospitalfoundation.ca.

00:10:36.172 --> 00:10:55.029
<v Casey>Four million dollars raised locally for equipment a rural hospital needs but doesn't automatically get — that's not a small number for a region this size, and it's the kind of steady, unglamorous civic work that rarely makes headlines but keeps a hospital functioning.

00:10:56.029 --> 00:11:02.457
<v Riley>Speaking of where decisions actually get made locally — that's exactly where we're headed next.

00:11:02.757 --> 00:11:29.756
<v Riley>The Central Cariboo Arts Centre in Williams Lake is getting a two-phase art installation — a large mural painted directly onto the building's exterior facade, plus new signage, courtesy of the Central Cariboo Arts and Culture Society. That's a public building getting a public face-lift, and somebody had to say yes to it, somewhere along the line, before a single brushstroke went on.

00:11:30.056 --> 00:11:43.341
<v Casey>Somebody did. The question is who, and whether a resident who disagreed with the mural's design or placement had any real avenue to weigh in before it went on the wall.

00:11:44.141 --> 00:11:59.998
<v Riley>That's the question I actually want to dig into today. Not whether the mural itself is good — whether the process behind it is one an ordinary resident could trace, after the fact, if they wanted to.

00:12:00.298 --> 00:12:32.440
<v Casey>Let's put a very different test case next to it, then — Arts on the Fly, the music festival in Horsefly. It runs on a solar-powered outdoor stage on the banks of the Horsefly River, an important salmon-spawning site, organized entirely by volunteers, no city hall involved at any stage. Horsefly isn't incorporated. There's no council meeting where a resident can stand up and formally object to where the stage sits relative to the riverbank.

00:12:32.740 --> 00:12:46.025
<v Riley>Because Horsefly sits inside the Cariboo Regional District's electoral area system — one director represents that whole area, alongside a huge stretch of surrounding rural land and several other small communities.

00:12:46.325 --> 00:13:12.039
<v Casey>One director for an area that size means the accountability math is completely different than Williams Lake, where you've got a mayor and six councillors, each one accountable to a ward-sized slice of a city of roughly 10,700 people. If a Williams Lake resident is furious about council's choice, they know exactly whose name goes on the ballot next election.

00:13:12.339 --> 00:13:43.196
<v Riley>Except fewer formal checkpoints doesn't automatically mean worse governance. It can mean faster decisions. Arts on the Fly has run for years without needing to clear a multi-year municipal capital planning cycle just to approve a stage location. Williams Lake's mural, by contrast, almost certainly went through the arts society's board, a facilities conversation with whoever owns or manages that building, and probably a sign-off against the city's signage or heritage bylaws.

00:13:43.496 --> 00:14:09.210
<v Casey>Slower, sure. But at least theoretically traceable. If a Williams Lake resident wants to know why that mural got approved, there's a public body — the arts society's board minutes, city council records — where that decision is supposed to live on paper. Where's the equivalent paper trail for a stage built on a salmon river in an unincorporated hamlet?

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:41.395
<v Riley>Fair question, and there is an answer, even if it's not obvious. The regional district maintains land use bylaws for its electoral areas, and anything built near a watercourse in BC typically has to clear a riparian setback review under the provincial Riparian Areas Protection Regulation — that applies regardless of whether the community around it is incorporated. The Water Sustainability Act layers on top of that for anything touching the actual streamflow.

00:14:41.695 --> 00:15:05.266
<v Casey>Provincial rules enforced, in practice, by a regional district with limited compliance staff, covering an enormous rural footprint that stretches from Horsefly to the Chilcotin. Enforcement existing on paper isn't the same as enforcement happening on the ground, and it's definitely not the same as a resident being able to find out whether it happened.

00:15:05.566 --> 00:15:29.994
<v Riley>That's a real capacity problem, but it's a different problem than "no one decided." The decision rights exist on paper — riparian permits, regional district building permits where applicable. The actual gap is whether an ordinary Horsefly resident even knows those rules exist, or has any idea where to look them up if they had a concern.

00:15:30.294 --> 00:15:54.722
<v Casey>Which is functionally the same as having no process, from where a resident is standing. If the rulebook technically exists but nobody outside the regional district planning office has ever seen it applied visibly to a specific local decision, that's not meaningful accountability. That's a rulebook nobody reads, sitting in a filing cabinet somewhere in Williams Lake.

00:15:55.522 --> 00:16:30.664
<v Riley>Okay — here's where I'd actually push back on my own framing, though. Compare it honestly to the Williams Lake mural. How many Williams Lake residents have actually read the arts society's internal approval process, or know it exists at all? Formal doesn't automatically mean legible to the public. A council agenda item buried three pages into a PDF is barely more accessible than an unwritten regional district norm, if nobody's actually translating either one into something a resident would stumble across.

00:16:30.964 --> 00:16:31.964
<v Casey>Right.

00:16:32.264 --> 00:16:49.406
<v Riley>So maybe the real dividing line isn't incorporated versus unincorporated at all. Maybe it's whether any local institution — city or regional district — actually publishes its decisions in a form an ordinary person would go looking for, and finds.

00:16:49.706 --> 00:17:38.563
<v Casey>That's closer to the real question, I'll give you that. Though I'd still say incorporation matters for one specific thing that doesn't disappear even with better publishing — recourse. If a Williams Lake resident hates the mural, they can show up at a council meeting, put their objection on the public record, and that record follows the sitting councillors into the next election cycle whether they like it or not. A Horsefly resident who hates where the festival stage sits has no equivalent lever to pull. The regional district director represents dozens of scattered communities — Horsefly's specific concern is one voice among many geographically dispersed constituencies competing for the same director's limited attention.

00:17:38.863 --> 00:18:09.291
<v Riley>Which is actually a structural argument for something concrete — a community advisory body specific to Horsefly. Not a new layer of government, not a budget ask, just a documented local voice that formally feeds into the regional district's electoral area planning discussions. Some BC electoral areas already have exactly that: unincorporated community associations without legal authority, but with a standing, recognized seat at the table when planning decisions come up.

00:18:09.591 --> 00:18:12.162
<v Casey>Does one exist for Horsefly today?

00:18:12.462 --> 00:18:27.890
<v Riley>Not that's documented in anything in front of us. Which is itself the actual finding here — the tool exists elsewhere in BC's regional district system, it's just not confirmed as active in this specific case.

00:18:28.790 --> 00:18:47.218
<v Casey>Then that's a concrete thing worth someone actually checking, rather than either of us assuming an answer on air. Whether the Cariboo Regional District has a registered community association or advisory structure specifically for Horsefly, distinct from the electoral area director's general mandate.

00:18:47.518 --> 00:19:11.946
<v Riley>And whether the Central Cariboo Arts and Culture Society's approval process for something like this mural — who signs off, what public notice happens before paint goes on an exterior wall — is published anywhere a Williams Lake resident could actually find without having to phone city hall directly and ask a staffer to explain it verbally.

00:19:12.246 --> 00:19:34.960
<v Casey>Two different governance models, but the same underlying test in both cases. Not "was a decision made" — obviously one was, in both Horsefly and Williams Lake. The real test is whether a resident who wasn't in the room can find out how that decision got made, after the fact, without insider knowledge.

00:19:35.960 --> 00:20:02.102
<v Riley>Which is a genuinely different question than the ones we've circled around on this theme before. This isn't about whether public input gets ignored once it's given, and it isn't about volunteers quietly propping up institutional gaps. It's narrower than either of those — it's about whether the decision itself leaves a trace anyone outside the process can actually follow later.

00:20:02.402 --> 00:20:24.259
<v Casey>And on that specific test, I don't think either Williams Lake or Horsefly clearly wins. One's got a formal process that exists but is genuinely hard for an outsider to find. The other doesn't have a formal process to find in the first place — it's relationships and volunteer memory instead.

00:20:24.559 --> 00:20:42.130
<v Riley>Which, notably, is a different failure mode than the one we've flagged before on this show — that one was about person-dependent systems collapsing when the person leaves. This is about the trace never existing at all, regardless of who's involved.

00:20:42.430 --> 00:20:57.858
<v Casey>Right, and that distinction matters, because the fix is different too. You can't formalize a relationship that was never written down to formalize in the first place — you have to build the record from zero.

00:20:58.758 --> 00:21:36.472
<v Riley>If there's a concrete next step here, it's not a grant application and it's not a volunteer ask — it's genuinely simple. Someone files a records request, or just sends a direct email to the regional district, asking two plain questions: is there a registered advisory body for Horsefly specifically, and where does the arts society publish its internal approval process for public installations. That costs nothing, needs no budget line, and it actually answers the traceability question instead of either of us guessing at it on air.

00:21:36.772 --> 00:21:53.057
<v Casey>That's a smaller ask than most civic reform pitches we've talked about on this show, and it's the kind of thing an actual resident could genuinely do this month, without waiting on anyone's grant cycle or anyone's permission.

00:21:53.357 --> 00:22:06.214
<v Riley>It's also the kind of question that'd make a good one to raise directly with a regional district director at a public meeting, rather than assuming the answer either way.

00:22:06.514 --> 00:22:15.514
<v Casey>Agreed. And it beats speculating about it from a podcast studio that's never once sat in on one of those meetings.

00:22:16.314 --> 00:22:39.885
<v Riley>If you've got a correction on how the regional district's electoral area advisory structure actually works, or a story tip about a local decision that never quite made it into any public record, send it to feedback at cariboo signals dot c-a — we'd genuinely like to know what we got wrong here, or right.

00:22:40.185 --> 00:22:50.470
<v Casey>And with that, we'll leave the paper trail question open for now — it's a better place to land than pretending we've solved it.

00:22:50.770 --> 00:23:02.769
<v Riley>Hope you're having a great weekend, and if you're anywhere near Fiftynine Creek or up around Anahim Lake, stay close to the official channels, not the rumour mill.

00:23:03.069 --> 00:23:06.926
<v Casey>Take care out there, Cariboo. We'll see you tomorrow.